1
00:00:08,660 --> 00:00:12,500
The other day, my family mailed me a bike helmet from Amazon.

2
00:00:13,119 --> 00:00:18,260
We used two-day shipping, and when the package arrived, it was essentially a cardboard box

3
00:00:18,260 --> 00:00:19,079
nesting doll.

4
00:00:19,579 --> 00:00:23,960
I had to cut my way through three different boxes in order to get to the helmet, which

5
00:00:23,960 --> 00:00:29,839
is especially ridiculous when you consider that a helmet is specifically designed to withstand

6
00:00:29,839 --> 00:00:30,519
and damp.

7
00:00:31,219 --> 00:00:37,460
With the holiday season fast approaching, which in the US means a rush of last minute Amazon

8
00:00:37,460 --> 00:00:43,799
prime orders just like mine, I feel it's important to look at the exact effect this new world

9
00:00:43,799 --> 00:00:48,259
of online shopping and instant shipping has on climate change.

10
00:00:50,399 --> 00:00:55,539
The carbon footprint of online shopping greatly depends on the actions of consumers.

11
00:00:56,539 --> 00:01:03,020
As a 2013 MIT study shows, shoppers can be divided into a number of different categories

12
00:01:03,020 --> 00:01:09,099
that span from a traditional retail shopper to what the study calls a cybernotch shopper,

13
00:01:09,280 --> 00:01:11,500
who exclusively shops online.

14
00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:16,840
The study shows that online shopping with slower shipping options has a smaller footprint

15
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:21,599
than driving to a retail store to search, purchase, and return a product.

16
00:01:22,599 --> 00:01:25,560
The highest impact shopper is actually a mix of both.

17
00:01:25,920 --> 00:01:31,000
One that goes to the store to compare prices and then buys online with expedited shipping.

18
00:01:31,560 --> 00:01:35,760
The majority of the reason why traditional shoppers have such a large footprint is that

19
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:38,719
they're using a car to reach these brick and mortar shops.

20
00:01:39,280 --> 00:01:44,900
So if they take public transportation, bike, or even walk, they're footprint plumbers.

21
00:01:45,340 --> 00:01:50,159
As for people who shop online, when they choose shipping options like two-day mailing,

22
00:01:50,159 --> 00:01:54,280
they are more than doubling their transportation-related emissions,

23
00:01:54,900 --> 00:01:59,459
especially within the last couple of years as companies like Amazon have started to send

24
00:01:59,459 --> 00:02:05,420
vans out to deliver packages that are only half full in order to fulfill customer expectations.

25
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:10,520
This ultimately means more emissions because trucks and vans have to make multiple trips

26
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:16,180
between hubs and homes, as opposed to slower shipping options which fill up trucks with cargo

27
00:02:16,180 --> 00:02:22,599
and make a single trip to fill orders. Packaging also has a significant role to play

28
00:02:22,599 --> 00:02:28,039
when it comes to environmental impact. Often when you select the two-day shipping option,

29
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:33,300
the products that you want aren't bundled together in the same box because they are usually

30
00:02:33,300 --> 00:02:38,300
coming from two different facilities across the country. As a result, you receive a new cardboard

31
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:45,460
box for every product you purchase. And the carbon emissions of products are on average 35% more

32
00:02:45,460 --> 00:02:51,159
when shipped separately than when shipped together. In addition, many products are packaged

33
00:02:51,159 --> 00:02:57,280
inefficiently. A study conducted by a peerless research group found that on average boxes contain

34
00:02:57,280 --> 00:03:04,719
20% of wasted space, which shipping facilities then fill with paper, styrofoam, or bubble wrap,

35
00:03:05,099 --> 00:03:10,199
ultimately creating more waste which finds its way into waterways or landfills.

36
00:03:10,919 --> 00:03:16,740
But there are many options on both the retail and consumer side that could help lower emissions.

37
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:22,740
For companies, cutting down emissions means nudging shoppers towards slower shipping options

38
00:03:22,740 --> 00:03:28,960
or making in-store purchases when appropriate. It can also mean bundling items together in one package

39
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:34,919
or even reducing the amount of packaging for a product by right sizing its box.

40
00:03:35,780 --> 00:03:39,800
But as individuals, we also have choices to make. For one, if it's possible,

41
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:45,419
find a way to get to your local retail store without using a car. You'll not only drastically

42
00:03:45,419 --> 00:03:50,960
lower your footprint, but Shopping Local also gives you the opportunity to connect with other people

43
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:56,699
face to face, which helps build community resilience in the long run. If you don't have that luxury,

44
00:03:57,060 --> 00:04:02,620
consider using slower shipping options, which allows the online retailer to optimize shipping

45
00:04:02,620 --> 00:04:07,340
routes because they don't have to rush to get the item onto your doorstep. This essentially means

46
00:04:07,340 --> 00:04:13,180
fewer miles traveled for trucks and planes because they can fill up with packages and only leave

47
00:04:13,180 --> 00:04:19,740
when they're full. Online Shopping isn't something to be demonized. It's an important resource for

48
00:04:19,740 --> 00:04:26,079
folks who may not be able to shop in person for a variety of reasons. However, it's important to

49
00:04:26,079 --> 00:04:32,160
think critically about our individual relationships with online shopping. I know I say this a lot,

50
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:38,699
but think before you shop. That online shopping spree not only has negative consequences for your

51
00:04:38,699 --> 00:04:43,980
wallet, but it also has lasting effects on the natural world we've come to rely on.

52
00:04:48,759 --> 00:04:52,779
Thanks so much for watching. If you've enjoyed the videos I've been putting out lately,

53
00:04:53,199 --> 00:04:57,339
consider clicking the subscribe button down below and hitting the little bell next to it.

54
00:04:57,620 --> 00:05:01,519
Or if you're feeling generous, the number one thing you could do to help this channel out

55
00:05:01,519 --> 00:05:08,600
is to support it on Patreon. Again, thank you so much for watching and I will see you in two weeks.

